        "content": "<p>I have searched mathlib for Scott domains, but I have not found any relevant definition.  More specifically, I am looking for fixpoint theorems, ie. theorems that state that, for instance, there exists a domain D such that</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>+</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">D = D + [D → D] + 1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>where <code>+</code> is the reduced sum, and <code>[D → D]</code> is the domain of continuous maps from <code>D</code> to itself.</p>",
